{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_moser_ver01/data/sn85025371/00542867322/1930082801/0700.xml":{"full_text":"1\nThe Clarke Courier\nR. N. Dorsey, Publisher\nf KMnblhlicd In i860 l>y Capt. Wm. K.\nNelson; owned and edited by the\nlate John O. Crown and Joseph\nW. Crown for more thun 84 years.\nEntered at the Postofflce at lierry\nfllle, Vu., .as second-clsss mail ttnt*\n'ter.\n*.50 Per Year In Advance\nEMERGENCY CROPS\nFOR STOCK FEED\nThe Commission on Drought Re\nlief has received so many Inquiries\nas to what farmers can do t\u00b0 meet\nthe feed shortage that the chairman\nhas requested Director John\nHutcheson, member of the commit\ntee to prepare a special statement on\nSis subject. Mr. Hutcheson has\nconsulted the members agron\nomy department of the Virginia E\nperiment Station, and makes the\nfollowing statement:\n-Owing to the lateness if the sea\nion, there is little hope that any\ncrop may be seeded after this date\nwitS the certainity^tha^ a^rop fQOf\nforage may aggured\nwould have an abundance of ram\nand that frost would not come earl\nier than the average frost date, we\nmight still sow such crops as millet,\nbuckwheat, and early soybeans, but\nAugust and September are normally\nmonths of light rainfall nothing\nbut a very unusual sueas\u00b0n \u2122Uabove\nsure sufficient growth of the above\nmentioned crops before, frost to jus\n!?y seeding them. For this season\ni/is thought that the best hope foi\nshortening the feeding season is\nto sow cereals and winter legumes,\nwhich will afford some grazing late\nin the fall and again in the spring\nbefore pasture is ready. The\ning crops are suggested.\nAbruzzi Rye.\u2014Abruzzi rye sown\nduring the last week of August 01\nthe first half of September will be\nready for grazing November bl\nand may be grazed until hard freez\ning weather comes. Under normal\nseason 30 to 40 days of grazing may\nbe expected from this variety of rye\nafter November first. The rye will\nbe ready for grazing again at least\nthirty days before Permanent pas\ntures have made sufficient spring\ngrowth to afford a full feed.\nBarley.\u2014Barley seeded during\nSeptember will afford considerame\nwinter grazing, though less than\nAbruzzi rye, and will produce an\nearly grain which may be used as a\nsubstitute for corn next summer. If\nbarley is sown for grain alone, clo\nnot sow until September 15, but n\nit is to be grazed as soon as ready\nsow any time during the month.\nVetch, Crimson Clover and Aus\ntrian Winter Feas.\u2014These crops\nmay be sown up to within two weeks\nof the average killing frost date it\nthe section. They afford early\nspring grazing or may be cut for\nearly hay. The proper rates ot\nseeding are 40 pounds of vetch, la\npounds of crimson clover, or\npounds of Austrian winter peas to\nthe acre. Seed should be inoculated\nand ,300 pounds of superphosphate\nshould be used as a fertilizer for\neach acre sown.\nMixture of Small Grains and Le\ngumes.\u2014Abruzzi rye and Hairy\nwinter vetch sowed at the rates ot\none bushel of rye and twenty pounds\nof vetch to the acre up to October\n10 will make good fall and early\nspring grazing, or may be cut for\nearly hay. Fertilizer recommenda\ntions are the same as for rye.\nWinter oats and Austrian winter\npeas sowed at the rates of, forty\npounds of oats and forty pounds ot\npeas make a good early spring hay\nif seeded during Sqptembey. Winter\noats seeded alone during September\nwill give grain foi* summer feeding.\nWhere wheat is on hand and\ncheap, it may toe. \u00bbeea$a auu^ t\u00abu\nweeks earlier than usual at. the rate\nof six to seven pecks to the acre aud\ngrazed until March without much\ndamage to next year\u2019s grain crop.\nHowever, it will not furnish more\nthan half as much grazing as a sim\nilar acreage of Abruzzi rye.\nRape seeded during August and\nSeptember at the rate if six pounds\nto the acre with winter oats or alone\nwill afford pesturage for hogs and\nsheep within forty days and may be\ngrazed' until hard freezing weather.\nRape requires a fertile sweet soil\nand should not be sown on acid soil\nManure or a complete' fertilizer in\nliberal quantities are advised.\nTurnips seeded during August at\nthe rate of 5 to 6 pounds to. the acre\nwill give roitB for storage if weather\nIs favorable. Or if 'no roots are\nmade, the tops may be grazed. Tur\nnips require about the same soil\nconditions as those mentioned for\nrape.\nWhere last springs clover and\ngrass seedings were killed by dry\nweather .,the soil may be disked and\nre-seeded to the same mixtures any\ntime up to within thirty days of the\naverage killing^ frost, hateJ These\nlate summer and early fall seedings\nwill give cuttings at the sanpie time\nnext summer that they would have\nbeen cut had the spring seeding\nlived through. If ops-half pound or\nturnip seed are spprh~,.t6 each here\nwith the grass se^p, a' goqd .crop of\nturnips may be gathered this fall\nwithout damage to the grass.\nM Mr and Mrs. Congreve Jackson\nand Mr. Congreve Jackson^ Jr., spent\nseveral days during the Horse Show\nat ''Woodbine\u201d. Mr.-Jackson, who Is\nMaster of Hounds of the Blue Ridge\nHunt was one of the'judges at' the\n\u00bb\u00abvrjrVille Hors^* Show.\nMANY RECENT GUESTS\nREGISTER AT WOODLAWN\nRecent gueBts registered at Wood\nlawn Tea House were Mr. and Mrs.\nT. W. Jenkins, Montclair, N. J.;\nMrs. Dallas Tucker, Mrs. Edward\nCooke, Mr. and Mrs. W. F. Alexan\nder, Charles Town; Ruth Kraft\nHazen, Mrs. R. F. Kraft, Miss Doro\nthy L. Schneider, Chicago; Mrs. J.\nD. Winter, Leland, Miss.; Mrs. C. G.\nBeck, Charles G. Beck, Mary W.\nBowly, Atlanta, Geo.; Mrs. J. S.\nPowers, Berry ville; Roberta Witner,\nLeLand Miss.; Thomas Lester Jor\ndon, New York City; Mrs. W. R.\nTalbot, Winchester; Cornelia H.\nIngersall, New York City; Frances\nBenjamin Johnston, Washington;\nGladys Harvey and sister, Gladwyne\nPa.; Lydia Y. Henning, Newark,\nDel.; Dr. and Mrs. S. T. Young.\nMiddleburg, Va.; Ann K. Rissler,\nCharles Town, Meredith Capper,\nWashington, Harry C. Smith, War\nrenton; Ernest Woolf, Upperville;\nMrs. Janie M. Lee, E. B. Lee, White\nPost; Mrs. Victor S. Ross, Davids\n.ville, Md.; Mrs. Charles McC. Math\nias, Miss Virgini aCarty, Frederick,\nMd.; Julia E. M. Smith, Bluemont;\nMiss Gertrude R. Meem, Washing-,\nton; Miss Mabel C. Massey, Ernest,\nF. Meade, White Post; Miss Eleanor\nPotts, Shepherdstown*. Mr. and Mrs.\nH. H. Williams, New York, N. Y. j\nMrs. George W. Eb^ugh, Misses j\nLaura and Deborah Ebaugh, Green- j\nville, S. C.; Mrs. Evett Wallace and\nson, John, Bethesda, Md.; Miss R.\nJ. Washington, Mrs. Walter H. Lee,\nEleanir Janet Lee, Thos. Girard Lee\nWashington; John S. Kausler, Miss\nSallie Kausler, Hagerstown, Mr. and\nMrs. B. L. Byers. Berry ville; Mr,,\nand Mrs. J. W. Manning, Mr. and!\nMrs. H. C. Hegelheimer, Luisley j\nHegelheimer, Niagara Falls, Canada\nB. F. Ristine, Dayton, O.; W. H. j\nRistine, Crawfordsville, lnd.i F. E.\nMcCutifo, Washington; Frederick:\nShepherd Taylor, E. F. i Taylor,\nWashington; Edward Choate O\u2019Dell,\nJames T. Leib, Mr. and Mrs. Her\nbert F. O\u2019Dell, Baltimore; Mrs. c\".\nH. Consilvo, Mrs. Buchard, Balti\nmore; Mr. and Mrs. Pauli S. Shields,\nHagerstiwn; Miss Anna Riddle, Mary i\nG. Dale, Charles own, W. Va.\nFavorite\nof a Famous Che\"\nas Told to Anre Befae\nEy LOUIS DIAT. Cm\nThe Ritz Carlton, New Yota\nSweet potatoes on the men:;\noften present a problem, as so\nfew variations in their prepara\ntion are offered in.the recipes at\nLouis Diat\nme command\nof the house- j\nwife. Here are\ntwo ways of\ncooking them\nthat Mr. Piat\nis particularly\nproud of.\nSweet Po\ntatoes Louisi\nana or South\ne r n Style\u20144\nportions\u2014Boil\nsix medium\nsized sweet po\ntatoes until\ntender in a generous quantity of\nsalted water. Cool, peel and cut\nIn round slices one-quarter inch\nthick. Arrange them in a shallow\nround earthenware or glass bak\ning dish, overlapping each other\nin circles. Brush with butter and\npour over them one-halt cupful of\nhot maple syrup and brown for\nfifteen minutes. Just before serv\ning, sprinkle with two tablespoons\nof sugar. Glaze for one or two\nminutes under a hot broiler.\nSweet Potatoes and Ananas\ni Louisiana Prepare sweet po\ntatoes -in the same manner as\nSweet Potatoes Louisiane. Ar\nrange them in the baking dish\nwith half slices of pineapple. Add\nmaple syrup, heat and glaze with\nsugar as above.\nDISTANCE TYPING\n\u2014I\nTelephone typewriter* are much\nlike the busy madblnes found In ban\ndreds of thousand* of office* in every 1\npart of the country But typewriter* j\noperated on telephone lines make it\npossible foi stenographers a; given\nlocations to transmit letters to one\nor more widely separated places, bet\nters are reproduced at the distant\npoints exactly as jttaey are typed on\nthe originating machine Teletype\nservice is widely: used by hanking\nbouses, cbaln businesses, manitfacthr\ning Industries, and state and metro\npolitan police departments.\n--0\nMr. and Mrs. Scott Thrope, and\ntheir daughter and son, Miss Marion\nand Wllmer Thrope, are spending\nseveral weeks at White Sulphur\nSprings\nMEMORIAL MEET\nFOR ROOT. E. LEE\nDirectors From Twenty Fi\u00ab\nStates and Many National Of\nficials To Be Present\nStratford, Va., Aug. 27.-\u2014Gover\nnor John Garland Pollard Mill be\nthe guest of honor and will deliver\nan address at Stratford Hall the af\nternoon of October 12th, when Rob\nert E. Lee Memorial Foundation\nholds the second annual celebration\non the anniversary of the death of\nGeneral Lee. In accepting the invi\ntation, extended by Mrs. Charles D.\nLanier, president of the Memorial\nFoundation and Mrs. Ambrose C.\nFord of Clifton Forge, Virginia\nState Director, Governor Pollard\nwrote that it would give him pleas\nure to be present upon an occasion\ndevoted to the memory of Lee.\nDirectors from twenty-five mem\nber states, and national officials and\nother prominent people, are expected\nto be present at the celebration,\nwhich will be held on the lawn in\nfront of .the mansion.\nDr. Henry Louis Smith former\npresident of Washington hnd Lee\nUniversity, the office once held by\nGeneral Lee, will deliver an address\non General Lee\u2019s life and character\nRev. Giles B. Cooke, ninety-two\nyear old civil war veteran and last\nsurvivor of General Lee's staff, will\nhave charge of the religious part of\nthe program. Mrs. Charles D. Lain\ner will preside.\nStratford is situated on the Poto\nmac river, 66 miles from Richmond\nand 44 miles from Fredericksburg,\nand is one of the oldest unaltered\nmanor homes in America. It was\nbuilt in 1729 and has never been re\nmodeled. General Lee, son of\nLighthorse Harry Lee of the Revolu\ntion, was born there in 1807. He\ndied at Lexington, where he is bur\nied, October 12, 1870.\nThe celebration on the anniver\nsary if General Lee\u2019s death is one of\nfour annual events held each year at\nStratford Hall, which is being made\na shrine by the Robert E. Lee Me\nmorial Foundation.\n---a\nSir Thomas Upton Tries Again.\nAmerica's Cup is again at stake as\nSir Thomas Lipton, the doughty Irish\nsportsman;\" brings the Shamrock V\nagainst the American defender in his\nfifth attempt to carry home the\nworld-famous yachting triphy. A\nthrilling account of the past races in\nthis classic contest to capture the\nmost coveted of all sporting prizes is\ngiven by Ralph McCabe in the Magar\nzine of The Washington Star\nSunday. Eb\n-0-:\nMiss Dorothy W. Randolph, vfhn\nspent the past week as the guestXof\nMiss Virginia Jacobs, returned Qtd\nher home, \u201cOld Welborne\u201d, n$af:\nUpperville on Sunday afternoon\n--=\u00a3\u00b1l.\nTULSA, OKLAHOMA v\nREPOTS UNUSUAL HEAT\nHot yesterday, wasn\u2019t it?V One\nhundred and forty-two thousand\nTulsans groaned and agreed. But\neven so\u2014and the weatherman wants\nthis made clear\u2014it was three de\ngrees cooler than the day before.\nThat was some relie?. Yesterday\u2019s\nhigh mark was 4 mild 104.\nTulsa has no cirner on the heat,\nthough. Those steeling pavements\nin the city were more than matched\nby popping popcorn on at least one\nstate farm, impossible? Well\u2014\nScience said it couldn\u2019t be done\nand proved it\u2014theoretically. But\nPittsburg county cornfields care lit\ntle for science and even less for\ntheory. That\u2019s one reason popcorn\nwas popping on the stalk down near!\nMcAlester last week. The other\nreason was the heat.\nWhen 15-year-old it. B. Tinker\ncame strolling into the little town\nof Beache from his nearby farm\nhome during the vfeek, his bare feet\nblistered by a sun-baked highway,\nwith a story of sun-popped popcorp\nthere were those that doubted him.\nSo R. B. braved the heat .again for\na round-trip home and back to bring\nin his proof.\nHe carried in the two stalks of\ncorn\u2014stalks he chopped from hte\nown popcorn patch on his father\u2019s\nfarm after last week\u2019s torrid temper\natures swept the state. It was\nenough to cure the doubters.\nJust what answer science will\nmake to R. B.\u2019s argument is still\nundetermined. It\u2019ll have to be\ngood though; Pittsburg county has\nseen popcorn popped on the stalk.\nScience says it can\u2019t be c^one? \u201cWho\u2019*\nthey\u2019re asking at Bache, \"is this guy\nscience?\u201d\nThe above is a clipping grom the\nTulsa Daily Weekly (Oklahoma) of\nSunday, August 17 handed to the\nj Courier by Mr. Hobson McGehee of\nAudley Farm.\n\u2014\u2014\u2014A\nBANK CLOSING\nMonday, September 1, being a\nlegal holiday, this bank will not be\nopen for transaction of business. All\npapers maturing on that date may be\narranged on the next succeeding bu\nafnofls Hnv\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK\nBANK CLOSING\nMonday, September 1, being a\nlegal holiday, this bank will not be\nopen for transaction of business. All\npapers maturing on that date may be\narranged on the next succeeding bu\nsiness day.\nBOYCE STATE BANK\n-0\nBANK CLOSING\nMonday. September 1, being a\nlegal holiday, this bank will not be\nopen for transaction o